Recommendation/Insight

Key findings show that higher stress levels correlate with decreased interest in Data Science (RQ1), and having more friends is associated with lower stress (RQ2). Open-mindedness and social bonds are recommended to minimize stress, supported by data analysis and external studies on academic stress and friendships.

The data was derived from a voluntary, anonymous questionnaire. The questionnaire adopts the method of randomising question blocks to ensure the comprehensiveness and validity of data. The purpose was to examine the behaviours of students in data science classes at the University of Sydney. The dataset contains 533 rows and 30 columns, giving the dataset a dimension of 30. The relevant variables include âInterest in Data Scienceâ (quantitative discrete), âStress Levelâ (quantitative discrete) and âFriends Count at USYDâ (quantitative discrete). Limitations in the dataset include self-selection bias and confounding variables impacting the validity of the study. Being a voluntary survey, only those students who give their consent are going to form part of the study, potentially allowing for systematic errors as a result of self-selection bias. For example those who are willing to partake in the study are likely more studious and may have a higher interest in the subject. It can be hypothesised that stress level may rise as interest in data science decreases, and linearity may be assumed between Friend count and stress allowing for use of the regression model. As for extreme error values social desirability bias can be assumed, where one may have had a fluctuating mood or may have altered their response due to their social surroundings. From the datasetsâ 30 variables, our research only focuses on 3 variables: friends count, stress level and data interest. We may clean it by isolating those variables, removing the rest. However, there is some missing data somewhere in each column, so we first must identify these values and remove them.

Does stress level affect participantsâ interest level in data science ?

It is recommended that students approach Data Science with an open mind in order to minimize stress level. Figure 1 presents a histogram investigating the relationship between Stress level 0-10 (Quantitative discrete) and Interest in Data Science 0-10 (Quantitative Discrete). At stress level 0 the median data interest is 6.5 and at stress level 10 the median data interest decreases to 5. In alignment with the âHowULearnâ (2016) Study from University of Helsinki referenced in the ScienceDirect Article titled âUniversity students interest and burnout profiles and their relation to approaches to learning and achievementâ, University students with higher cynicism to learning represented higher levels of exhaustion. This is referenced with figure 2 as stress level 10 exhibits a decreased median interest in data science of 5. Limitations of the graphical summaries (Fig. 1 and 2) provided include confounding variables such as date of study prior to any exam period potentially reducing median stress level, as well as previous studies of data science which may have overlapped with current content reducing workload stress. Thus, Figures 1 and 2 support the recommendation of open mindedness to Data Science in order to decrease stress, the recommendation remains reliable based on external studies such as the âHowULearnâ Study from University of Helsinki.

library(tidyverse)

survey_data <- read.csv("data1001_survey_data.csv")

survey_data <- survey_data %>%
  select(friends_count, si_1, data_interest._1)

survey_data <- survey_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(friends_count) & !is.na(si_1) & !is.na(data_interest._1))

survey_data$si_1 = as.factor(survey_data$si_1)
ggplot(survey_data, aes(x=data_interest._1)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill=si_1), 
           color = "black"
           ) + 
  labs(x="Data interest", 
       title="Data interest vs Stress level",
       subtitle = "Figure_1"
      ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(-1, 11), 
    breaks = seq(0, 10, 1)
  ) +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")
ggplot(survey_data, aes(x = data_interest._1, y = si_1)) +

    subtitle = "Figure_2"
  )  +

    limits = c(0, 10),

Is having more friends associated with lower stress ?

It is recommended in order to decrease stress level in studies of Data Science to make more friends for social and study purposes. The residual plot (Figure 1) shows constant homoscedasticity indicating that linear regression should be appropriate. Figure 2 represents friend count against stress level in a scatterplot with a regression line. The Correlation Coefficient (r) in figure 2 is -0.17, indicating a weak negative correlation between the two variables. The least squares regression line has a steady downward slope indicating a negative linear relationship, supporting the hypothesis that decreasing friends results in increasing stress level. These findings are directly supported by the USA National Library of Medicine, stating âBuilding robust social bonds among classmates within educational institutions can reduce stressâ, explored in their mass data summation, âThe Benefits of Friendships in Academic Settings: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysisâ (2023). Limitations within this data may include social desirability bias, where number of friends may have been recorded incorrectly due to desirability of a socially acceptable amount of friends at USYD. In summation the data presented shows an increase in stress level as friend count lowers encouraging the initial suggestion of making more friends in order to decrease stress levels.

library(tidyverse)

survey_data <- read.csv("data1001_survey_data.csv")

survey_data <- survey_data %>%
  select(friends_count, si_1, data_interest._1)

survey_data <- survey_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(friends_count) & !is.na(si_1) & !is.na(data_interest._1))

model = lm(friends_count ~ si_1, data = survey_data)

ggplot(model, aes(x= .fitted, y= .resid, color = "#ADD8E6")) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, 
             linetype = "dashed", 
             colour = "black") +
  labs(title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values for Friends Count Based on Stress level", subtitle="Fig_1") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "linen"))
ggplot(survey_data, aes(x=si_1, y=friends_count, color = "#ADD8E6")) + # Specify x and y variables
  geom_point() + # Create scatter plot
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE, color = "blue") + # Add line of best fit
  labs(x="Stress level", y="Firend Counts", title="Friends Count vs Stress level", subtitle="Fig_2")+
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 10), breaks = seq(0, 10, 1)) +
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue"))
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
